**Developing a Telegram‑Based Group‑Chat Fund/DAO – A Comprehensive Plan for 2025**  
  
**1 Vision and Concept**  
  
The goal is to transform a Telegram group chat into a cooperative **group‑fund/DAO** where members can collectively deposit crypto funds, propose and execute trades, and manage governance *within Telegram*. Such a system should feel like a multiplayer game, yet provide serious financial tooling. Instead of individuals executing trades through single‑player Telegram bots, the group‑chat fund will use programmatic roles, multi‑signature (multisig) wallets and on‑chain governance to allow several members to control pooled capital.  
The **NinDAO** proposal on Safe’s forum illustrates how this vision can work. The proposal describes a “next‑generation DAO management” system where a Telegram bot bridges **WalletConnect**, **Safe multisig**, and **Telegram** so that users can create proposals, gather votes and execute transactions directly inside the chat . By integrating account abstraction, the bot intends to simplify Web3 usage, making Safe management more accessible while preserving decentralization and security .  
Your project seeks to develop a similar system but for a group‑chat hedge fund: members deposit into a shared treasury; authorized traders execute trades through DEX aggregators; governance and permissions are managed on‑chain; and membership is controlled via token gating or role assignments.  
  
**2 Key Components and Recommended Tools**  
  
To build this ecosystem, the project should combine several open‑source tools, frameworks and best practices from Web3 and Telegram development.  
  
**2.1 Telegram Bot Framework**  
	•	**grammY (Node.js / TypeScript)** – A modern Telegram bot framework that emphasizes type safety, consistent support for the latest Bot API, comprehensive documentation and a plugin ecosystem . grammY is recommended over older frameworks like Telegraf because it is well‑maintained and scalable . It can be extended with middlewares for session management, throttling and input parsing.  
	•	**python‑telegram‑bot / Telethon** – For teams preferring Python, these libraries provide mature Telegram Bot API support and asynchronous programming models .  
  
**2.2 Multisig Treasury and Account Abstraction**  
	•	**Safe (formerly Gnosis Safe)** – The de‑facto multisig smart account used by DAOs. Safe allows customizable thresholds for transaction approval, gasless transactions, batching and account recovery .  Modular **Safe modules** add automation, whitelisting and rate‑limiting but should be thoroughly audited .  
	•	**Zodiac** – A standard for modular DAO tooling built on Safe. It introduces **avatars** (smart accounts like Safe) and **modules** that implement decision logic; for example, the **Governor module** turns a multisig into a multiplayer DAO with on‑chain voting  . Zodiac also provides cross‑chain modules (e.g., Bridge) for bridging funds between EVM chains.  
	•	**Hats Protocol** – An on‑chain role management system. Hats allows DAOs to **grant, revoke and transfer signing authority** over Safe multisigs to individuals, committees or councils . Roles can be tied to elections or token holdings, enabling dynamic onboarding/offboarding of traders and governors. Case studies show Hats being used to allocate veto power to security councils or manage grants across multiple domains .  This solves the challenge of rotating signers and limiting risk when traders leave.  
  
**2.3 DAO & Governance Frameworks**  
	•	**Aragon** – Provides an intuitive platform with customizable governance frameworks, treasury management and permission settings, letting users create autonomous organizations without writing complex code .  
	•	**DAOstack** – Offers scalable governance with **holographic consensus** and reputation‑based voting . Suitable for large communities needing efficient decision‑making.  
	•	**Colony** – Designed for task‑based DAOs with project management, reputation and funding flows; ideal if you want to track contributions and distribute rewards .  
	•	**Snapshot** – A gasless off‑chain voting platform used for signal voting; token holders sign messages to vote and can change votes before the deadline 【394560192622944†L168-L166】. Snapshot integrates easily with Safe (via SafeSnap) and is widely adopted in 2025, enabling proposals to be approved in Telegram and executed on‑chain.  
	•	**Tally** – An on‑chain governance dashboard that provides real‑time analytics and proposal insights . Use Tally when decisions need to be executed directly on-chain and tracked publicly.  
  
**2.4 Membership and Token‑Gating**  
	•	**Collab.Land** – A bot service that verifies token or NFT ownership and assigns roles in Telegram groups. Collab.Land can gate entry based on ERC‑20 balances or NFT attributes . Setup involves adding the @collablandbot as an admin, granting it permissions and configuring token‑gating rules via the dashboard .  Collab.Land supports more than 40 chains and 30 wallets .  
	•	**Guild.xyz or Token Gated Channel** – Alternatives offering similar functionality with custom rules and cross‑platform support.  
	•	**SBT/POAP tokens** – The DAO could mint non‑transferable Soulbound tokens (SBTs) or distribute Proof‑of‑Attendance (POAP) badges to represent membership tiers or participation streaks.  
  
**2.5 Trading Infrastructure & DEX Aggregators**  
	•	**DEX aggregators** – To execute trades, use a trusted aggregator offering the best on‑chain liquidity and MEV‑protection.  Options include **1inch**, **ParaSwap** and **OpenOcean**; these services aggregate quotes across many decentralized exchanges and provide SDKs for integration.  The Rubic blog emphasises using transparent routing and MEV protection—ParaSwap and Odos are highlighted for efficient routing and transparency  .  
	•	**QuickNode DeFi bundle** – QuickNode provides an API with gas estimation, MEV protection and cross‑DEX swaps (via OpenOcean) used in their Telegram trading bot guide .  The sample project uses the **viem** library to sign transactions, **better‑sqlite3** to store encrypted keys, and grammY to implement commands  .  Adapt this architecture for multi‑user trading via the DAO.  
  
**2.6 Smart Contract Development & Security**  
	•	**OpenZeppelin Contracts** – Use battle‑tested smart contract libraries (ERC‑20, ERC‑721, Multisig factory, AccessControl) and security patterns such as SafeMath and the checks‑effects‑interactions pattern to prevent reentrancy .  
	•	**Hardhat or Foundry** – For contract development, testing and deployment. Hardhat integrates with Ethers.js and has plugin ecosystems; Foundry is a Rust‑based toolchain popular in 2025.  
	•	**Static analyzers** – Tools such as **Slither** and **Mythril** can detect vulnerabilities in Solidity contracts .  
	•	**Auditing & bug bounties** – Before mainnet deployment, conduct external audits and consider a bug bounty program. The article on smart contract security notes that once deployed, contracts cannot be changed; major hacks result from poor audits .  
  
**2.7 Legal & Regulatory Considerations**  
	•	Choose a DAO jurisdiction (Wyoming DAO LLC, Cayman Foundation, Swiss Association or Singapore VFA). The 2025 DAO guide notes that Wyoming recognises DAOs as legal entities, while Switzerland and Singapore offer supportive frameworks .  
	•	Clarify tax, liability and reporting obligations; consult legal experts to structure your DAO and comply with securities laws.  
	•	Consider using an investment club framework like **Syndicate**, which helps DAOs create legal wrappers for investment clubs and integrates with Safe to manage capital (note: accessible sources summarising this may be limited).  
  
**3 Designing the Group‑Chat Fund/DAO**  
  
## **3.1 Roles & Permissions**  

| Role | Description & Tools |
| ------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Member/Contributor | Any Telegram user permitted into the group. Membership is enforced via Collab.Land token‑gating or SBT gating. Members can contribute funds, view treasury activity and vote on proposals via Snapshot; they cannot execute trades directly. |
| Trader (Delegate) | Designated individuals with permission to propose and execute trades. Traders are assigned a “trader hat” through Hats protocol, granting signing authority on the Safe multisig . The Hats role can be revoked or transferred if the community votes to replace a trader. |
| Manager/Administrator | Oversees the bot, manages Collab.Land settings and controls off‑chain integrations. They also maintain the off‑chain database used by the Telegram bot. |
| Governance council / multisig signers | Individuals or committees who sign transactions proposed by traders. The Safe multisig threshold should be at least 2/3 to prevent unilateral actions. Hats roles can automate signer rotation and delegate veto power (as Purple did for its security council) . |
  

